HIGH SCHOOL DISTANCE LEARNING: Clarification on the classroom procedures-
Teachers will have a Google Meet established for each class, each day in Google Classroom.
Distance Learning students must be present via Google Meets at the beginning of class time, each class period Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday.
Teachers will take daily attendance based on participation in Google Meets for distance learners.
Students are expected to stay in Google Meets as long as teacher requires.

post_text: We are deeply saddened by the unexpected loss of high school paraprofessional Brenda Schutte on Sunday. Brenda was a dedicated part of the Isle Schools community, well-liked by students, and admired by her co-workers. Our deepest sympathies go out to Brenda's family in this time of great loss. Students who knew and worked with Brenda and who wish to talk about this loss should contact the high school office or counselor Kate Turner.

To assist us in our planning we need your help! A very important survey has been sent out to you asking about educational planning for your family. We need information on learning model choices to inform transportation needs and health issues all of which will help us keep students and staff safe and keep our schools open for students.

Please look for and promptly complete the 2020-2021 school commitment and planning survey which was sent to families via email today (August 6). If you do not receive a survey, or have other questions regarding the 2020-21 school year, please call the District Office at 320-676-3146 or email Mr. Kapsner at dkapsner@isle.k12.mn.us.

post_text:
We too were anxiously awaiting the governor’s announcement today. We will be reviewing the guidance and going through the plans that we have been compiling.

Isle school board and staff will meet on Monday, August 3 to discuss the governor's announcement on the reopening of schools and what that means for our local plan.

We plan to have students in school as much as possible provided we can do so safely.

Thank you for your continued support. Go Huskies!

Summer Rec practices are getting started!

T-Ball's first practice is tomorrow (Thursday, June 11). Preschool and younger players practice from 5:00-5:45, Kindergarten and older players practice from 6:00-6:45.

13U Baseball also has their first practice tomorrow from 6:00-7:30.

11U Baseball's first practice will also be next week: Date and time TBD as we're still looking for a coach or two willing to help out!

Also a reminder that It's never too late to register for Summer Rec!

- Online courses are available
- Small class sizes and a faculty and staff that know students by name

post_text: As the school year winds down and we transition into summer we recognize that many families face unique hardships this year. As a way of support, the school will provide a limited meal program throughout the summer months. The program will provide breakfast and lunch items for each child, three days per week. . Should you choose to participate, meals must be picked up at the school on Mondays between 12:00 and 1:30 pm. Meals will no longer be delivered to homes. To sign up please use the survey link below or email Lyz Habeck at: ehabeck@isle.k12.mn.us with the number of children 18 or under that will be participating. Please register by tomorrow, Thursday, May 28th for the Monday, June 1st meal pick up. You can still register for meals after this Thursday but pick up will be for the following Monday, June 8th. Once registered, more information will be provided. SURVEY LINK: https://forms.gle/Rvefgey2e6c24CDD8

post_text:
Dear Parents/Students,
I am happy to reach out to you today with exciting news! Even in times of social distancing, the yearbook signing tradition lives on. Today Jostens has launched Yearbook Digital Signing Pages, a one-of-a-kind web experience that provides students with a fun and interactive experience that results in a printable permanent keepsake. It's available and free for all students whether they purchased a yearbook or not. Check it out! https://yearbooksigning.jostens.com/home

May 19 at 3:31 PM ·

Video 4 of 4 (Socially Distant Graduation Visit)
❤️🐾 We had an AWESOME school year with our preschoolers! We wanted to share a few videos with some of our fun memories from school, our Fun Foodie Fridays, distant learning and our socially distant preschool graduation. Thank you all for a great year! We are so proud of all of our preschool graduates! Have a fun summer!🐾❤️
Love, Mrs. Remer & Mrs. Schoeck

*Preschool families you will all be receiving a copy of these videos in DVD format in the mail.

post_text: Ruby’s Pantry in Onamia, Mn (806 West Kathio Street) is having a pop-up pantry on Monday, June 1st. Registration begins at 10am and is hosted by Bethany Lutheran Church. Food bundles are available from 10:30-12:00pm. Due to COVID-19 Mille Lacs Lakes Area Operation Community Connect provided by Mille Lacs Area Health Foundation has partnered with Ruby’s Pantry to distribute bags with resources and a meal to bring home. Families can choose to participate in one or both of these events. This is a drive thru event and supplies are limited.

post_text:
We have some exciting news! The Yearbooks are here! Yearbooks will be sent home next Friday, May 22nd during the homework delivery for students that have ordered them! If you have not ordered a yearbook it is not too late! Yearbooks are $60 and you can call and pay directly at the district office (676-3146) or mail your check or money order to the school (Isle High School, Attn: Yearbook advisor, Box 25, Isle, MN 56342)

We also need photos from YOU during this Distance Learning time! Photos of you and your family on how you are spending your time, what you are doing from getting bored, indoor fun, outdoor fun, projects etc. These pictures can be emailed to kmellon@isle.k12.mn.us
Thanks so much and remember we will get through this together!
Kim Mellon, Yearbook Advisor

post_text:
COVID-19 Youth Forum This Friday

We’re asking for your help in spreading the word that the Minnesota Youth Council will be hosting a COVID-19 Youth Forum THIS FRIDAY, May 15. The forum will be streamed live on the Minnesota Alliance with Youth Facebook page from 3:30 - 4:30 p.m. The discussion will focus on providing information to students about distance learning, how to access support and more. Learn more about the event on their Facebook page.

Thank you!

Minnesota Department of Education

post_text:
We are looking to hire a Technology Assistant & Support Specialist to work within the district. Please share this post.

APPLICATION PROCESS:

A complete and qualifying application will consist of the following:
•Letter of application
•Current Resume’
•Official education transcripts (if applicable)
•Three letters of recommendation

Submit application materials to:
email: klasart@isle.k12.mn.us
US mail: Kelly LaSart
P.O. box 25
Isle, MN 56342

Application Deadline:
Applications must be received either electronically or by U.S. mail no later than 4 pm on May 22nd.

**Successful applicant will be required to complete a background check prior to employment.

post_text:
Are you ready for another video? Team Orange!

Have you ever wondered what the staff gets up to in their free time? This year Mr. Kapsner challenged us to our first ever Covid Cure Challenge.... The staff was split into teams and challenged to create videos under the categories of feats of strength, extreme lounging, ballin' around, hangin with animals, fun with food, me make music, power parenting, expressive dance, motor sports, gymnastics, lawn/water sports, and the great outdoors. We'll try to get a video up from all the teams we can. In the meantime, sit back and enjoy.... see if you can identify the staff members.... but don't take us to seriously... We miss you all!

post_text:
We know graduation and all of the events leading up to it are sacred to our students and families. We have not forgotten all the other stuff that goes along with graduation.

Tentative information:

Senior BBQ - We hope to reschedule it after the stay-at-home order expires

Senior Week, July 13-17, 2020

We are working with the Minnestrial group to reschedule Senior Breakfast and Baccalaureate.

Senior Scholarship Night - Though individual scholarships may communicate with the recipients beforehand, we plan to recognize scholarship recipients during Senior Week in July.

Graduation - Ceremony specifics still need to be worked out and will be heavily influenced by guidance from the state. We are planning for a ceremony and perhaps other special events on July 17th.

post_text:
HIGH SCHOOL: Midterm report cards are being emailed Wednesday!

With guidance from MDE and in doing the best we can with Distance Learning,
We will still be using letter grades of A, B, and C.
We will issue a grade of "P" (Pass) for students earning 60-69%
We will issue a grade of "NC" (No Credit) for students earning below 60%.
The grades of "P" and "NC" will not be used for calculating student GPAs.

post_text:
THANK YOU Mr. Kapsner, Ms. Maxwell and Mr. Schultz!

Governor Tim Walz has issued a proclamation making today School Principals Day. Minnesota recognizes our outstanding elementary, middle level and high school principals who have succeeded in providing high-quality teaching, learning, and working conditions for our students, educators and school staff. Thank you for all of your work and leadership!
text:

post_text:
Grades 9-11 Virtual College Fair

On April 23 during two different time slots your students can attend an online college fair to help them connect with top schools around the country -- without needing to leave their homes.

Students can tune in to two panel discussions:

“Tips on Creating Your College List”
“Behind the Scenes: How Admissions Decisions Are Made”

They can drop into virtual rooms where admissions officers from more than 40 schools will share information about their college and answer questions in real time.

Learn more and register for this free event, recommended for students in grades 9-11.

The event is hosted by the Coalition for College and features schools that meet the organization's affordability and student success criteria.

http://coalitionforcollegeaccess.org/april-2020-virtual-fair.html

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Education
April 15 at 10:00 AM ·

The Minnesota Department of Education is excited to be a partner for the new statewide book club, One Book | One Minnesota. Throughout April and May, Minnesotans of all ages are invited to read a common title and come together virtually to enjoy, reflect and discuss. The first book selection is New York Times bestseller and Newbery Honor winner “Because of Winn-Dixie” by Minnesota’s own Kate DiCamillo. Each week, local libraries will be hosting online discussions about the book. Digital copies of the book will be available on Ebooks Minnesota for eight weeks, at no cost. Visit your local library’s website to learn more. #onebookmn

McQuoid's Inn and Event Center
March 16 at 1:48 PM ·

UPDATE***
We will now be serving in our event center located in the hotel.
We have secured to-go boxes, if you have the means to communicate that you will be coming and can let us know in advance then we can have it ready for you. This will help us limit how many people gather at once.
With the local schools shutting down we understand that many in our local and surrounding communities will be working less and would appreciate a meal . We would like to offer those in need, especially those with children, free dinner between 6pm and 8pm on the following dates: Thursday March 19 hot beef sandwiches and macaroni salad, Monday March 23 Heggies Pizzas, and Thursday March 26 spaghetti with a meat sauce. We will also provide apple juice, fruit punch, and tap water. Feel free to bring your own drinks as well, no alcohol please. Meals will be in our Cedar Room. We are not a restaurant so what we offer is all that we will have available.

post_text:
Bridges 2020 Career Exploration Day!
Central Lakes College, Brainerd Campus
March 6, 2020 -- For all 10-12th grade students!
The Bridges Career Exploration Day is designed for high school students to learn about careers. Students will be able to attend presentations, see demonstrations and have some hands on experiences from women and men who work in a variety of career fields. The following is a partial list of careers that will be represented: Nursing / Healthcare, Financial Advisor/Banking, Commercial Art (Graphic Design), Photography, Welding / Manufacturing, Drafting, Heavy Equipment, Computer Technology, Engineering, Broadcasting/News Reporting, Machine Trades and Construction, Marine/Small Engine, Law Enforcement, Massage Therapy, Robotics, Automotive Service Technology, Journalist/Reporter, DNR, Floral Design, Daycare Professional, Dental and Small Business Entrepreneur.

post_text: The Raider wrestlers had a great showing on Saturday at the Section 7A Tournament. The team was led by Braldey Bernu who won four matches and was a runner-up at the 152 pound weight class and is now qualified for the State Tournament this Friday at the Excel Energy Center. Brad won his first three matches to grab a spot in the finals where he lost a tough 7-6 match. This meant Brad had to wrestle a True-Second match to qualify for state. Brad wasted little time and took control of the match and won easily 20-4. Eric Thompson, Ethan Benson and Daniel Miller all just missed a chance to go to state and each brought home third place. Cam Wilkes and Josh Golombowski each won three matches and placed fifth. Congrats to all of the guys on a great season!

ALC students went to the state table tennis tournament this weekend.

David Lester, Noah Miller, Matthew Miller, Hunter Biros, Lacee Gamer, Steve Rosekrans, Jeannette Smith, Chloe Holscher and Spencer Davenport combined with players from Onamia and Minneapolis to create a team.

Thanks for playing with us Onamia student Matthew Smart!!
